The jury took less than three hours to come to a guilty verdict.

Over the course of the investigation Smithey's accounts of what happened varied.

At first she told officers the gun had gone off by accident, but she then changed the story to say she had actually pulled the trigger. 

Assistant State Attorney Stacey Salmons told jurors there was no rape and argued that she inflicted the cuts on herself. 

Some witnesses who were at the scene described Smithey as crying and hysterical, but paramedic who rode with her in an ambulance believed she acting.

A nurse who performed a rape exam on her in the aftermath said she thought she had been a victim of sexual assault. 

